da .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud was born about 1311. She married Stephen de Okeley Lord of Okeley about 1328, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters."},"et":{"about 1311–":"umbes 1311–Surnud","1309–Male":"1309–Surnud","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","1339–Male":"1339–Surnud","1311–Female":"1311–Surnud","1337":"1337","about 1329":"umbes 1329","1311":"1311","Abt 1337":"umbes 1337","1363":"1363","about 1311":"umbes 1311","1309":"1309","ABT 1328":"umbes 1328","Abt 1339":"umbes 1339","1329":"1329","1339":"1339","of Okeley, Stafford, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","of Okeley,Stafford,England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1311–":"noin 1311–Kuollut","1309–Male":"1309–Kuollut","1329–1363":"1329–1363","1337–Female":"1337–Kuollut","1339–Male":"1339–Kuollut","1311–Female":"1311–Kuollut","1337":"1337","about 1329":"noin 1329","1311":"1311","Abt 1337":"noin 1337","1